title: For Sale/Trade:  Browning Double Automatic Twelvette Model
postcontent:
Hello Guys,

Up for sale is a Browning Double Automatic Twelvette Model. Blond wood. Barrel is 27 1/2" with modified choke and ventilated rib. LOP is 14 1/4" from front of trigger to middle of original buttplate. Stock is uncut with no recoil pad. Total weight unloaded is 7lbs 4 5/8 ozs.

Condition is very good to excellent and has been fired very little. You can tell how often one of these guns has been fired by the wear on the gold plated trigger and the wear on the side of the receiver where you chamber the shells. The loading port will eventually wear through the anodization and show as silver around the edges when the gun has been loaded (and shot) a lot. This gun still has the full gold trigger plating and very little wear around the loading port. Black anodization is still fully intact which indicates usage (loading) on the low to very low side.

No major scratches on the metal or dents on the wood anywhere - just usual handling and wear marks, but in remarkable overall condition. No splits or cracks in the stock or forearm anywhere. I purchased the gun about 6 years ago and fired it only once to make sure. I purchased it because of its quality condition. I have another DA I shoot and no longer desire this one.

For those of you who may not be familiar, this gun was designed by John Browning's son Val Browning as an option to double guns. People often wonder "why a 2-shot automatic?" The reason was to have a gun as fast or faster than a S by S or O/U with less weight.  These guns are often misunderstood. It seems shooters either "get them" or they don't. If you "get it," you tend to love them and regret parting with them. 

These guns are extremely reliable and I have never experienced a single jam or misfire except for reloads when the brass was not properly resized. 

The Browning Double Auto’s are a fast loading lightweight and fast shooting gun at home in the field or with clays. Personally, I love these guns as I am a southpaw and I can load the gun very quickly while holding it inches from my shoulder. Safety is located on the back of the trigger guard so the gun is truly ambidextrous. They tend to kick a little due to recoil operation and light weight.

Asking $1,000 or best reasonable offer. Also may be willing to accept trades.

Thanks for looking and contact me for questions or more pics.

Mike

D. Removable Front Sight: Allows user toreplace existing sights with accessory sight systems or replace damaged sight.

E. Internal Recoil Buffer: Increases servicelife by reducing stress on the receiver createdby the more powerful .40 S&W ammunition.

H. Caliber Availability: The 90-Two is available in both the 9mm and the .40 S&W.

I. Accessory Rail: The frame of the 90-Two has a Picatinny MIL-STD-1913 rail for rapid attachment of tactical lights and laser aimingdevices. Includes removable rail cover.

title: For Sale:  Colt DA 38 1903
postcontent:
I 1908 my grandfather emigrated to the US from Norway landing first in Halifax Canada then traveling the St. Lawrence seaway to Chicago.  

In Chicago he set about buying a horse, wagon, supplies and provision to travel west.  One of his purchases is the 1903 Colt DA 38 presented in this advertisement.  Embarking Chicago in his wagon he traveled to Elk City South Dakota where he met and married my grandmother, also a Norwegian immigrant.  Together they set out across the Sioux Nation lands deep into the heart of the Dakotas with that Colt DA 38 strapped to his hip to purchase land, start a ranch and raise a total of 15 children.  

A bit about the revolver specifics.  It features a counter-clockwise rotating cylinder, which can be opened for loading and ejection by simply pulling back on a catch mounted on the left side of the frame behind the recoil shield. It is easily manipulated by the thumb of the right hand, and upon release the cylinder can be poked out sideways with the shooter's forefinger. Empty cases are removed by simply pushing back on an ejector rod to activate a star extractor. The six-shooter could then be quickly reloaded and the cylinder clicked back into place.

One interesting thing about this particular revolver is the inspector’s mark on the left top of the frame: "J.T.T." for John Taliaferro Thompson, designer and father of the famous submachine gun that bears his name. He was a U.S. Government arms inspector before becoming famous for his sub-machine gun.  This revolver also bears the engraving R.A.C. which is US Gov't Inspector's mark of Rinaldo A. Carr on the frame and the smooth walnut grips.

This revolver was designed to shoot 38 Long Colt and 38 Short Colt ammunition.

Holster included.
